<text>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd">
&lt;html>&lt;head>&lt;meta name="qrichtext" content="1" />&lt;style type="text/css">
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style>&lt;/head>&lt;body style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;">
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">George III&lt;/p>
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">King of England from 1760 to 1801, George III penned this letter to Nawab Omdat-ul Omrah Mayeen ul Mulk to offer his condolences for the death of Muhammed Ali Khan Wallajah (who passed on 13 October 1795). The offering of such condolences on the King’s part perhaps was owed to his desire to solidify relations with the ruling classes of India.&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
