<text>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd">
&lt;html>&lt;head>&lt;meta name="qrichtext" content="1" />&lt;style type="text/css">
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style>&lt;/head>&lt;body style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;">
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">Nawab Omdat-ul Omrah Mayeen ul Mulk&lt;/p>
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">The recipient of this letter served as Nawab of the Carnatic State of the Mughal Empire from 1795 to 1801. The Carnatic State was one of the oldest imperial dependencies, but they had fallen on hard times since the 1760s, when, in response to the growing presence of foreign forces in their country, threw their support behind the British. Ul Mulk’s predecessor, Wallajah, had nearly bankrupted himself in offering this support. Rather than reimburse him for his efforts, the EIC ended up confiscating much of Wallajah’s land. Thus, we can imagine that ul Mulk would perhaps have not appreciated King George III’s rosy tone.&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
